"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 31–32
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-31-32.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing: chs 1–30 complete)

Key Christological decisions:
- Ch31 focuses on the covenant God's faithfulness in the face of Laban's treachery;
  key connections are the Immanuel promise (v3/v5), the "God of Bethel" theophany
  (v13 returning to 28:12-17), the contrast of the living covenant God with Rachel's
  stolen teraphim (idols, v19), and the Mizpah covenant as a boundary witness (v49).
- The "Awe/Fear of Isaac" (pahad Yitzhak, vv42,53) is an unusual divine title,
  possibly meaning "the God whom Isaac revered" or "the Kinsman of Isaac" — treated
  here as a revelation of God as the one who inspires reverent fear, fully revealed
  in Christ who is both the Lord to be feared and the one who removes fear (Rev 1:17).
- Ch32 Peniel wrestling (vv24-32) is treated as a Christophany — the pre-incarnate
  Son of God wrestling with Jacob. Hosea 12:3-5 confirms "the angel" in this episode
  is the LORD God Almighty. John 8:56-58 ("Abraham rejoiced to see my day") suggests
  the patriarchal theophanies involve the Son. The divine self-limitation (unable to
  overpower Jacob until he touches the hip, v25) anticipates the kenosis of Phil 2:7.
- Jacob's prayer (32:9-12) is treated as the model of intercessory prayer: appeals
  to covenant promise, acknowledges unworthiness, asks for specific rescue.
- The wrestling "clinging" (v26 — "I will not let you go unless you bless me") is
  explicitly connected to Luke 18:1-8 (the persistent widow); faith that holds on.
- The name Israel (v28) = new identity through divine encounter; pattern of the
  new name Christ gives (Rev 2:17); and the limp (v31) = mark left by God-encounter,
  structurally similar to Paul's thorn (2 Cor 12:7-10).
- Peniel (v30 — "I saw God face to face") vs. Exod 33:20 ("no one may see me and
  live"): resolved in 2 Cor 4:6 — God's glory is seen "in the face of Christ."
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-christ commentary for Genesis 31–32, covering Jacob's flight from
#   Laban and return to Canaan (ch31), and the Jabbok wrestling/Peniel theophany
#   (ch32). The Peniel encounter is the Christological peak: Hosea 12:4 calls
#   the wrestler "the angel" and "the LORD God Almighty"; John 8:56-58 places
#   Christ in the patriarchal encounters.
# CHANGE? If data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json structure changes, update
#   load_comm/save_comm in Z_COMMENTARY_SCRIPT_GUIDE.md.
# VERIFY: python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json')); print(len(d.get('31',{})), len(d.get('32',{})))" should print "55 32".

NEW_DATA = {
"31": {
"1": "<p>Jacob hears that Laban&#8217;s sons resent his prosperity &#8212; the accusation that he took what was Laban&#8217;s. The irony is that Jacob prospered not through theft but through divine multiplication (vv8&#8211;9). The prosperity of the covenant bearer is misread by those outside the covenant as exploitation. The same misreading attends the church&#8217;s growth: &#8220;these men who have caused trouble all over the world have now come here&#8221; (Acts 17:6). The rising resentment in Haran is the pressure that will move Jacob back toward the land of promise &#8212; divine providence using opposition to accomplish the return.</p>",
"2": "<p>Jacob notices Laban&#8217;s changed attitude &#8212; the deterioration of the relationship that signals the time to leave. The covenant people&#8217;s life among those who do not share the covenant is always provisional; the relationship that seemed stable shifts when the covenant heir&#8217;s prosperity becomes undeniable. The alien and stranger status of the covenant people &#8212; &#8220;I have been a foreigner in a foreign land&#8221; (Exod 2:22) &#8212; is the condition in which the call to return home is most welcome. The changed face of Laban is the providence that prepares Jacob to hear the call of v3.</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;The LORD said to Jacob, &#8216;Go back to the land of your fathers and to your relatives, and I will be with you.&#8217;&#8221; The divine call to return &#8212; the Immanuel promise renewed. The promise &#8220;I will be with you&#8221; echoes 28:15 (Bethel: &#8220;I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go&#8221;) and anticipates Matt 28:20 (&#8220;I am with you always, to the very end of the age&#8221;). The God who commanded the exile also commands the return; the God who accompanied the departure accompanies the homecoming. Christ is the permanent Immanuel: Heb 13:5 &#8212; &#8220;I will never leave you nor forsake you.&#8221;</p>",
"4": "<p>Jacob summons Rachel and Leah to the fields &#8212; away from the household, where the conversation will not be overheard. The covenant head gathers his household to tell them of the divine call. The pattern of the shepherd gathering the flock to lead them home: &#8220;he calls his own sheep by name and leads them out&#8221; (John 10:3). Jacob&#8217;s summons to his wives is the summons to follow the divine call regardless of what is left behind &#8212; the same summons Christ issues: &#8220;come, follow me&#8221; (Matt 4:19), leave the familiar and follow toward the promised inheritance.</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;The God of my father has been with me.&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s testimony of divine faithfulness in the face of Laban&#8217;s hostility &#8212; retrospective recognition of God&#8217;s accompanying presence. The testimony of God&#8217;s past faithfulness is the ground of confidence for the future. Paul&#8217;s confident declaration &#8220;he who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion&#8221; (Phil 1:6) is the NT form of Jacob&#8217;s &#8220;the God of my father has been with me.&#8221; The God who was with Jacob in the twenty years of exploitation is the God who will be with him on the journey home and in the meeting with Esau.</p>",
"6": "<p>&#8220;You know that I&#8217;ve worked for your father with all my strength.&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s claim of faithful labor &#8212; his integrity in service. Twenty years of complete dedication to Laban&#8217;s household (v41: fourteen for the wives, six for the flocks). The faithful servant who has served with his whole strength is the model of covenant faithfulness. Christ as the faithful servant who does the Father&#8217;s work &#8220;to the very end&#8221; (John 13:1): &#8220;I have brought you glory on earth by finishing the work you gave me to do&#8221; (John 17:4). Jacob&#8217;s claim of complete service anticipates the claim that Christ alone can fully make.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;Your father has cheated me by changing my wages ten times. However, God has not allowed him to harm me.&#8221; The divine protection of the covenant heir from the exploiter&#8217;s schemes. Laban changes the terms repeatedly; God overrules each change. The Lord&#8217;s protection of his people from those who would harm them &#8212; &#8220;no weapon forged against you will prevail&#8221; (Isa 54:17) &#8212; operates even through the natural processes of flock multiplication. Rom 8:28 &#8212; &#8220;in all things God works for the good of those who love him.&#8221; Laban&#8217;s treachery becomes the context in which divine faithfulness is most visible.</p>",
"8": "<p>The pattern of divine multiplication against Laban&#8217;s changing terms &#8212; &#8220;if he said the speckled ones will be your wages, then all the flocks gave birth to speckled young.&#8221; The covenant God&#8217;s blessing is not limited by the terms that others set. Whatever constraints the world places on the covenant heir, God works within those constraints to multiply and bless. The parable of the talents (Matt 25:14&#8211;30) operates on the same principle: the servant who receives even a small portion multiplies it through faithfulness. God&#8217;s blessing is not defeated by unfavorable terms.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;God has taken away your father&#8217;s livestock and has given them to me.&#8221; The transfer of wealth from the oppressor to the covenant heir &#8212; the Exodus pattern anticipated. Exod 12:35&#8211;36 &#8212; Israel left Egypt with the Egyptians&#8217; silver, gold, and clothing: &#8220;they plundered the Egyptians.&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s enrichment at Laban&#8217;s expense is the type of the covenant people&#8217;s enrichment at the expense of those who exploited them &#8212; a reversal pattern that the NT extends to the spiritual realm: the inheritance that Christ claims from the powers that held humanity captive (Col 2:15 &#8212; &#8220;having disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them&#8221;).</p>",
"10": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s dream of the streaked, speckled, and spotted male goats mating with the flock &#8212; the divine revelation that shaped his selective breeding practice. The dream that gave Jacob the strategy for prosperity is the divine guidance that the covenant heir receives. The God who guides through dreams (Joseph&#8217;s dreams, ch37&#8211;41; the magi&#8217;s dream, Matt 2:12; Joseph&#8217;s dream, Matt 2:13) is the God who provides his covenant people with wisdom for survival and flourishing in hostile circumstances. The dream of the goats is the wisdom from above (Jas 1:5) that outstrips Laban&#8217;s human cunning.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;The angel of God said to me in the dream, &#8216;Jacob.&#8217;&#8221; &#8212; The angel of God calling Jacob by name &#8212; the personal, name-knowing divine address. John 10:3 &#8212; &#8220;he calls his own sheep by name.&#8221; The angel who speaks in dreams to the patriarchs (28:12; here; 48:16) and the angel who speaks to Joseph in Egypt (Matt 2:13) are agents of the divine purpose that ultimately finds its full expression in the one who is himself the Word (John 1:1) &#8212; no longer angels in dreams but the Son who speaks in person (Heb 1:1&#8211;2).</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;I have seen all that Laban has been doing to you.&#8221; The divine witness to the covenant heir&#8217;s suffering &#8212; God sees what the oppressor does and acts accordingly. Exod 3:7 &#8212; &#8220;I have indeed seen the misery of my people in Egypt. I have heard them crying out because of their slave drivers, and I am concerned about their suffering.&#8221; The same divine attentiveness that sees Jacob&#8217;s twenty years of exploitation in Haran sees the suffering of the oppressed and moves to redeem. Christ&#8217;s incarnation is the ultimate expression of this seeing: he enters the suffering he sees and bears it himself (Isa 53:3 &#8212; &#8220;he was despised and rejected by mankind, a man of suffering&#8221;).</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;I am the God of Bethel, where you anointed a pillar and where you made a vow to me.&#8221; The divine self-identification connecting back to 28:10&#8211;22 &#8212; the God of Bethel is the God of the ladder/stairway, the God on whom the angels ascend and descend. Christ in John 1:51 identifies himself as the one the Bethel vision pointed to. The God who speaks at Bethel and now speaks in Haran is the same God &#8212; consistent, covenant-keeping, bringing the exile to a close. &#8220;Now leave this land at once&#8221; &#8212; the divine command to return fulfills the covenant promise of return (28:15: &#8220;I will bring you back to this land&#8221;).</p>",
"14": "<p>Rachel and Leah&#8217;s response &#8212; they feel like foreigners in their own father&#8217;s household, sold for Jacob&#8217;s service. Their alienation from Laban mirrors the exile condition of the covenant people. The women who have been treated as commodities in Laban&#8217;s house find their true belonging not in Haran but in the covenant community that Jacob leads. The covenant community is defined not by natural family ties but by the covenant itself: &#8220;there is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither slave nor free, nor is there male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus&#8221; (Gal 3:28). Rachel and Leah&#8217;s &#8220;do we still have any share?&#8221; is answered by the covenant inheritance in Christ.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;Not only has he sold us, but he has used up what was paid for us.&#8221; The economic exploitation of the covenant women &#8212; treated as property, their bride-price consumed by Laban. The NT context of redemption from exploitation: Christ &#8220;redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&#8221; (Gal 3:13). The language of redemption (<em>gāʾal</em>/<em>lytron</em>) in both testaments involves buying back what was wrongly taken. Those who have been sold and exploited &#8212; by sin, by the powers, by oppressive systems &#8212; are bought back by Christ&#8217;s blood (1 Cor 6:20 &#8212; &#8220;you were bought at a price&#8221;).</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;Surely all the wealth that God took away from our father belongs to us and our children.&#8221; Rachel and Leah confirm: what Jacob has accumulated is rightfully his and theirs, given by God. The covenant community&#8217;s inheritance is given by God, not earned by manipulation &#8212; yet they are also the rightful heirs. The tension between gift and rightful inheritance is the tension of the covenant: what God gives freely is also genuinely ours. Eph 1:11 &#8212; &#8220;in him we were also chosen, having been predestined according to the plan of him who works out everything in conformity with the purpose of his will.&#8221; The inheritance that the covenant heir carries is God&#8217;s gift and the heir&#8217;s rightful possession.</p>",
"17": "<p>Jacob puts his children and wives on camels &#8212; the departure begins. The exodus from Haran with family, flocks, and goods &#8212; the covenant household on the move. The departure pattern recurs through Scripture: Abraham from Ur (12:1&#8211;5), Jacob from Bethel and now from Haran, Israel from Egypt, the return from Babylon. The moving household of the covenant is always en route &#8212; the people of God are pilgrims. Heb 11:13 &#8212; &#8220;all these people were still living by faith when they died. They did not receive the things promised; they only saw them and welcomed them from a distance, admitting that they were foreigners and strangers on earth.&#8221;</p>",
"18": "<p>Jacob drove all his livestock and goods accumulated in Paddan Aram toward Canaan. The return journey carrying twenty years of covenant accumulation &#8212; the providential enrichment of the exile being brought home. The exodus from Egypt with the Egyptians&#8217; wealth (Exod 12:36) follows the same pattern. The covenant people do not leave the place of exile empty-handed: they carry the gifts that God multiplied during the exile. The church&#8217;s life in the world produces spiritual fruit (Gal 5:22&#8211;23) that will not be left behind &#8212; what God builds through his people is carried into the new creation (Rev 21:24&#8211;26).</p>",
"19": "<p>Rachel stole her father&#8217;s household gods (<em>teraphim</em>). The stolen idols are the contrast that frames the whole chapter: Laban worships the <em>teraphim</em>; Jacob worships the God who speaks in dreams and multiplies flocks. The worthlessness of idols compared to the living God is the subtext. Jer 2:11&#8211;13 &#8212; &#8220;my people have exchanged their glorious God for worthless idols.&#8221; The <em>teraphim</em> that Laban chases after &#8212; which are hidden under a saddle and sat on by a menstruating woman (v35) &#8212; are the humiliated idols that reveal the folly of worshipping objects made by hands. Christ replaces idols with the living God made known (1 John 5:21 &#8212; &#8220;keep yourselves from idols&#8221;).</p>",
"20": "<p>Jacob deceived Laban by not telling him he was leaving &#8212; the secret departure. The deceptive element in Jacob&#8217;s character recurs (cf. ch27) even as God&#8217;s covenant faithfulness does not depend on the moral perfection of the covenant bearer. The God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob works with and through people who are morally complex &#8212; which is the scandal of election and the mercy of grace. 1 Cor 1:27&#8211;29 &#8212; God chose the weak and foolish to shame the wise and strong, so that no one can boast. The covenant purpose is not sanctified by the character of the covenant people but by the character of the covenant God.</p>",
"21": "<p>Jacob crossed the Euphrates and headed toward Gilead &#8212; the first major geographical step of the return. Crossing the Euphrates (the boundary of Mesopotamia) is the decisive move &#8212; there is no easy turning back. The covenant heir committing to the return, crossing the boundary that separates the old life from the new. The decisive crossing parallels Israel crossing the Red Sea (the no-return point of the Exodus) and the Jordan crossing into Canaan (Josh 3&#8211;4). Christ&#8217;s &#8220;I have set my face to go to Jerusalem&#8221; (Luke 9:51) is the commitment to the return journey from which there is no retreat.</p>",
"22": "<p>Laban learned of the flight three days later &#8212; the gap that divine providence has opened. Three days of lead time for the covenant heir. The &#8220;third day&#8221; pattern runs through Scripture: three days in the grave before resurrection (Matt 12:40; 1 Cor 15:4). The three-day head start that Jacob receives is not merely logistical &#8212; it is the gap that divine protection has maintained. The &#8220;third day&#8221; is often the day of divine deliverance: Joseph in the prison three days (40:12&#8211;13), the three days of Esther&#8217;s fast before her approach to the king (Esth 4:16), the resurrection on the third day.</p>",
"23": "<p>Laban pursued Jacob for seven days and caught up with him in the hill country of Gilead. The seven-day pursuit &#8212; determined, relentless. The Pharaoh who pursued Israel with chariots; the Herod who killed the children seeking Jesus; the Saul who pursued David across the wilderness. The covenant heir is pursued, apparently cornered &#8212; and then divine intervention changes everything. The God who intervenes between the pursuer and the pursued (v24) is the God of Ps 23:5 &#8212; &#8220;you prepare a table before me in the presence of my enemies.&#8221;</p>",
"24": "<p>&#8220;God came to Laban the Aramean in a dream at night and said to him, &#8216;Be careful not to say anything to Jacob, either good or bad.&#8217;&#8221; God protects Jacob by restraining Laban &#8212; not through supernatural power but through a warning dream to the pursuer. The divine protection of the covenant heir extends even to restraining those who would harm him through the workings of their own conscience. Acts 5:38&#8211;39 &#8212; Gamaliel&#8217;s warning: &#8220;if their purpose or activity is of human origin, it will fail. But if it is from God, you will not be able to stop these men.&#8221; Those who oppose what God protects find themselves restrained, sometimes without knowing why.</p>",
"25": "<p>Laban caught up with Jacob and camped near him. The confrontation that seemed inevitable is now subject to divine constraint (v24). The two parties face each other with the word of God standing between them &#8212; Laban warned not to harm Jacob. The divine word as the unseen protection: &#8220;the LORD will rescue me from every evil attack and will bring me safely to his heavenly kingdom&#8221; (2 Tim 4:18). Christ as the divine word standing between those who would harm his people and the people themselves: &#8220;no one will snatch them out of my hand&#8221; (John 10:28).</p>",
"26": "<p>Laban&#8217;s complaint &#8212; &#8220;you&#8217;ve deceived me and carried off my daughters like captives in war.&#8221; The accusation of kidnapping has some surface plausibility but misreads the situation: the daughters themselves agreed to leave (v16). The world&#8217;s accusation against those who follow the divine call is always that they have been &#8220;taken&#8221; &#8212; that the covenant community has abducted its members from their proper allegiance. The NT accusation against the apostles is similar: &#8220;these men who have turned the world upside down have come here also&#8221; (Acts 17:6). The departure from Laban&#8217;s household is freedom, not kidnapping.</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;Why did you run off secretly and deceive me? Why didn&#8217;t you tell me, so I could send you away with joy and singing?&#8221; Laban&#8217;s imagined alternative &#8212; the joyful send-off he would have given. The irony is that this is precisely the send-off that Laban had not given and would not have given; Jacob fled because Laban would have prevented his departure. The world&#8217;s retrospective claim that it would have blessed what it actually tried to control is the claim that does not account for its own hostility. The gospel invitation&#8217;s &#8220;if only you had come sooner&#8221; does not acknowledge the barriers it erected.</p>",
"28": "<p>&#8220;You didn&#8217;t even let me kiss my grandchildren and my daughters goodbye.&#8221; Laban&#8217;s genuine grief at separation &#8212; the mixed motives of the man who exploited his daughters now missing them. The complexity of human relationships: Laban is both oppressor and grandfather, both greedy and genuinely attached. The pastoral realism of the OT narrative does not flatten human character into simple villain or hero. Christ&#8217;s incarnation enters this moral complexity &#8212; he does not come to a world of simple heroes and villains but to the genuinely tangled human situation in which love and exploitation coexist.</p>",
"29": "<p>&#8220;I have the power to harm you; but last night the God of your father said to me, &#8216;Be careful not to say anything to Jacob, either good or bad.&#8217;&#8221; Laban acknowledges the divine warning &#8212; his human power restrained by divine command. The boast of human power followed immediately by its limitation: &#8220;I have the power, BUT.&#8221; Every human power over the covenant people is subject to divine limitation. Rev 6:2&#8211;8 &#8212; even the four horsemen operate within the bounds of divine permission (&#8220;they were given power&#8221;). No power is absolute except God&#8217;s; every power that threatens the covenant community operates within the sovereign boundaries that Christ holds.</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;But why did you steal my gods?&#8221; Laban&#8217;s primary concern: the <em>teraphim</em>. The household gods that he trusts for guidance and protection have been taken &#8212; and he has traveled seven days to retrieve them. The contrast with Jacob&#8217;s God who has been actually present, actually speaking in dreams, actually protecting through the journey &#8212; a God who cannot be stolen, who is not confined to a house or a saddle. Isa 44:9&#8211;20 &#8212; the folly of idols: you cannot carry a god who carries you. The God who carries Jacob (Isa 46:4 &#8212; &#8220;I have made you and I will carry you&#8221;) cannot be carried off by a thief.</p>",
"31": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s honest explanation &#8212; he fled because he was afraid Laban would take his wives by force. The fear that drove the deception: flight born of fear rather than wickedness. The covenant heir&#8217;s flight is not treacherous but self-protective. The same fear-driven flight marks Moses fleeing to Midian (Exod 2:14&#8211;15) and David fleeing Saul (1 Sam 19:18). The one who does not flee from fear is Christ in Gethsemane: &#8220;not as I will, but as you will&#8221; (Matt 26:39) &#8212; facing the threat rather than fleeing, because his mission requires it.</p>",
"32": "<p>Jacob offers an unwitting death sentence: &#8220;if you find anyone who has your gods, that person shall not live.&#8221; Jacob does not know Rachel has taken them. The oath spoken in ignorance that creates danger &#8212; the covenant head&#8217;s words carrying more weight than he knows. The unintended consequences of speech in covenant contexts run through Scripture: Jephthah&#8217;s vow (Judg 11:30&#8211;39); the high priest&#8217;s unconscious prophecy about Christ (John 11:49&#8211;52 &#8212; &#8220;it is better for you that one man die for the people&#8221;). Words spoken in covenant contexts carry weight their speakers do not fully understand.</p>",
"33": "<p>Laban searches through Jacob&#8217;s tent, Leah&#8217;s tent, the servants&#8217; tents &#8212; and finds nothing. The comprehensive search that comes up empty is the type of the diligent seeking that finds nothing in a place where it never was. The <em>teraphim</em> are not in the places Laban expects because Rachel has hidden them. The contrast: Laban searches for his idols and cannot find them; Jacob seeks the LORD who has been consistently, obviously, manifestly present. Jer 29:13 &#8212; &#8220;you will seek me and find me when you seek me with all your heart.&#8221; The living God is found by those who seek; idols are lost when someone sits on them.</p>",
"34": "<p>Rachel had put the household gods inside her camel&#8217;s saddle and was sitting on them. The irony of the <em>teraphim</em> hidden under a woman&#8217;s saddle &#8212; objects supposedly sacred to divination and household protection, stuffed under a saddle and sat upon. The narrative&#8217;s dry humor is the humor of the prophetic critique of idols: &#8220;they have mouths, but cannot speak, eyes, but cannot see&#8221; (Ps 115:5). The gods that Laban relies on cannot cry out from under the saddle; Jacob&#8217;s God has been speaking in dreams, multiplying flocks, and restraining pursuers throughout the chapter.</p>",
"35": "<p>Rachel claims she cannot rise because she is having her period &#8212; she uses a socially acceptable excuse to avoid discovery. The deception that protects Rachel from Laban&#8217;s discovery. The narrative presents this without endorsing it &#8212; it is the ingenuity of the oppressed using available means to protect what they have. The situation Rachel is in (her father exploited her and would reclaim his idols) is one in which her deception is understandable, if not praiseworthy. The covenant narrative is honest about the moral compromises that survival in hostile conditions requires &#8212; without using them as models.</p>",
"36": "<p>Jacob, not knowing about the idols, angrily confronts Laban with twenty years of grievances: &#8220;What is my crime? How have I wronged you?&#8221; The anger of the genuinely innocent &#8212; Jacob does not know the <em>teraphim</em> are in his camp and so speaks with complete righteous indignation. The passion of his defense in vv36&#8211;42 is one of the great speeches of grievance in the OT. The righteous anger of the one who has served faithfully and been repeatedly exploited: &#8220;it is mine to avenge; I will repay, says the Lord&#8221; (Rom 12:19). The vindication Jacob seeks from Laban is the vindication that God himself provides.</p>",
"37": "<p>&#8220;What have you found that belongs to your household? Put it here in front of our relatives and let them judge.&#8221; Jacob calls for arbitration by witnesses &#8212; the appeal to communal judgment as the standard of justice. The covenant community operates by acknowledged standards of judgment rather than raw power. The NT pattern of church discipline: &#8220;if they still refuse to listen, tell it to the church&#8221; (Matt 18:17); the appeal to community judgment rather than self-help retaliation. Jacob&#8217;s call for witnesses before whom the matter can be laid is the call for accountability that covenantal community provides.</p>",
"38": "<p>&#8220;I have been with you for twenty years now. Your sheep and goats have not miscarried, nor have I eaten rams from your flocks.&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s account of faithful stewardship &#8212; twenty years without a miscarried animal, without taking from the flock for personal consumption. The faithful steward who has not exploited his position: Luke 12:42&#8211;44 &#8212; &#8220;who then is the faithful and wise manager, whom the master puts in charge of his servants to give them their food allowance at the proper time?&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s stewardship of Laban&#8217;s flocks is the type of the faithful stewardship Christ calls for in those who tend what belongs to another.</p>",
"39": "<p>&#8220;I did not bring you animals torn by wild beasts; I bore the loss myself.&#8221; Jacob absorbed the losses rather than passing them to Laban &#8212; the shepherd who takes personal responsibility for what is lost rather than making excuses. The good shepherd who &#8220;goes after the lost sheep&#8221; (Luke 15:4) and &#8220;lays down his life for the sheep&#8221; (John 10:11). The model of the shepherd who does not abandon the flock to predators but bears the cost of protection. Jacob&#8217;s &#8220;I bore the loss myself&#8221; is the type of Christ&#8217;s absorbing the cost of human sin rather than letting it fall on those he tends.</p>",
"40": "<p>&#8220;The heat consumed me in the daytime and the cold at night, and sleep fled from my eyes.&#8221; The physical cost of twenty years of faithful service &#8212; the extremes of temperature, the sleeplessness of vigilance. The shepherd who does not rest, who does not protect himself at the expense of the flock. Phil 2:17 &#8212; Paul describes himself as being &#8220;poured out like a drink offering.&#8221; The servant whose body bears the cost of the mission is the pattern that Christ fulfills: &#8220;the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&#8221; (Matt 20:28). Jacob&#8217;s heat-and-cold exhaustion is the physical form of the complete self-giving that the covenant servant&#8217;s mission requires.</p>",
"41": "<p>Twenty years &#8212; fourteen for the daughters, six for the flocks &#8212; and ten changes of wages. The specificity of Jacob&#8217;s grievance: he counts and remembers. The covenant God also counts and remembers: Rev 6:9&#8211;11 &#8212; the souls under the altar asking &#8220;how long?&#8221; are told to wait until the full number of their brothers and sisters is complete. The suffering of the covenant servant is witnessed and counted by God: &#8220;precious in the sight of the LORD is the death of his faithful servants&#8221; (Ps 116:15). The twenty years of Jacob&#8217;s exploited service are not forgotten by the God who said &#8220;I have seen&#8221; (v12).</p>",
"42": "<p>&#8220;If the God of my father, the God of Abraham and the Awe of Isaac, had not been with me, you would surely have sent me away empty-handed.&#8221; The &#8220;Awe of Isaac&#8221; (<em>paḥaḏ Yiṣḥāq</em>) &#8212; an unusual divine title appearing only here and v53. The term may mean &#8220;the God whom Isaac reveres&#8221; or possibly &#8220;the Kinsman/Protector of Isaac.&#8221; The God who inspires reverent fear is the God fully revealed in Christ who is simultaneously the one to be feared (Rev 1:17 &#8212; John falls as if dead before him) and the one who removes fear (Rev 1:17 &#8212; &#8220;do not be afraid&#8221;). &#8220;But God has seen my hardship and the toil of my hands, and last night he rebuked you.&#8221; Divine vindication arriving at the right moment.</p>",
"43": "<p>Laban&#8217;s response &#8212; &#8220;the women are my daughters, the children are my children, the flocks are my flocks.&#8221; The claim of comprehensive ownership that simultaneously acknowledges he can do nothing about it: &#8220;Yet what can I do today?&#8221; The world&#8217;s claim of ownership over what God has given to the covenant community &#8212; and the world&#8217;s helplessness before the divine decree. Laban&#8217;s &#8220;all you see is mine&#8221; is the claim of every Pharaoh, every Caesar, every dominating power over the people of God. The divine word that says &#8220;I will be with you&#8221; (v3) and &#8220;be careful not to harm Jacob&#8221; (v24) is what makes Laban&#8217;s comprehensive claim ultimately empty.</p>",
"44": "<p>&#8220;Come now, let&#8217;s make a covenant.&#8221; Laban proposes the formal resolution &#8212; a covenant boundary agreement. The covenant-making capacity of the human community &#8212; even between those in conflict &#8212; reflects the image of the covenant-making God. Gen 9:9 (God&#8217;s covenant with Noah), 15:18 (with Abraham), 17:4 (with Abraham again): the divine covenant-making is the original of which human covenant-making is the reflection. The covenant between Jacob and Laban is limited and self-protective; the covenant between God and humanity in Christ is unlimited and self-giving (Luke 22:20 &#8212; &#8220;this cup is the new covenant in my blood&#8221;).</p>",
"45": "<p>Jacob set up a stone as a pillar &#8212; the same gesture as at Bethel (28:18). The pillar as covenant marker &#8212; the stone that stands as witness. 1 Pet 2:4&#8211;7 &#8212; Christ as the living stone, the cornerstone. The stone memorials of the OT &#8212; Bethel, Mizpah, Gilead &#8212; are the type of the one permanent memorial that Christ erects through his death and resurrection: the Lord&#8217;s Supper. &#8220;Do this in remembrance of me&#8221; (Luke 22:19) &#8212; the permanent witness-stone of the new covenant community. Every covenant pillar that Jacob sets up points toward the one memorial that does not erode.</p>",
"46": "<p>The relatives gathered stones and piled them in a heap &#8212; the communal act of covenant-making. The covenant boundary is built by the whole community, not just the leaders. The communal construction of the covenant witness: the people of God are not passive recipients of a covenant arranged between the leaders but active participants in covenant life. The NT pattern of the body of Christ: &#8220;from him the whole body, joined and held together by every supporting ligament, grows and builds itself up in love, as each part does its work&#8221; (Eph 4:16). The communal heap-building is the type of the communal covenant life.</p>",
"47": "<p>Laban called the heap in Aramaic (<em>Yegar Sahadutha</em> = heap of witness); Jacob called it in Hebrew (<em>Galeed</em> = heap of witness). The same reality named in two languages &#8212; the two parties cannot yet communicate in one tongue. The linguistic barrier between the covenant community and the surrounding peoples anticipates the Babel problem (11:7&#8211;9) that Pentecost begins to resolve (Acts 2:6&#8211;11). The one thing they agree on &#8212; that the heap is a witness &#8212; is the common ground on which the covenant boundary is built. The common witness to what God has done transcends linguistic barriers.</p>",
"48": "<p>&#8220;This heap is a witness between you and me today.&#8221; The naming of Galeed confirms the function: the heap stands as a witness to the covenant agreement. The covenant God himself is the ultimate witness: &#8220;the LORD is witness between us&#8221; (Mal 2:14 &#8212; covenant of marriage). The God who witnesses the covenant between Jacob and Laban is the God who witnesses and guarantees the new covenant: Heb 7:22 &#8212; Jesus is &#8220;the guarantor of a better covenant.&#8221; The stone heap has a witness function that the incarnate Christ fulfills permanently &#8212; he is the living covenant witness who does not erode.</p>",
"49": "<p>&#8220;It was also called Mizpah, because he said, &#8216;May the LORD keep watch between you and me when we are away from each other.&#8217;&#8221; Mizpah &#8212; &#8220;watchtower&#8221; &#8212; as a covenant boundary marker invoked when the parties are separated. The LORD as the covenant-keeping watchman who monitors the agreement between parties who cannot monitor each other. The divine omniscience as the ground of covenant accountability. Christ as the one who knows &#8220;what is in each person&#8221; (John 2:25) and before whom &#8220;nothing in all creation is hidden&#8221; (Heb 4:13). The Mizpah blessing, often used in farewell, is originally a covenant boundary: the LORD watches to ensure neither party crosses the line.</p>",
"50": "<p>&#8220;God is a witness between you and me.&#8221; The appeal to divine witness as the ultimate accountability for the covenant. The covenant-making that relies on divine witness rather than human enforcement is the model of the new covenant: Christ as the &#8220;mediator of a new covenant&#8221; (Heb 9:15) who does not merely witness the agreement but guarantees it through his own blood. The God who watches between Laban and Jacob is the God who witnesses the new covenant and guarantees it through the death and resurrection of his Son. Human witness fails; divine witness endures.</p>",
"51": "<p>The heap and the pillar as double witness &#8212; the covenant boundary marked physically. The double witness principle (Deut 17:6; Matt 18:16) &#8212; two or three witnesses establish truth. The physical markers of the covenant boundary are the external confirmation of the internal covenant commitment. The new covenant has external markers too: baptism as the marker of entry into the covenant community (Acts 2:38; Rom 6:3&#8211;4) and the Lord&#8217;s Supper as the ongoing marker of covenant membership (1 Cor 11:23&#8211;26). The heap and pillar of Gilead point toward the sacramental markers of the new covenant community.</p>",
"52": "<p>&#8220;This heap is a witness, and this pillar is a witness, that I will not go past this heap to your side&#8230; and that you will not go past this heap and pillar to my side to harm me.&#8221; The covenant boundary is mutual &#8212; both parties agree not to cross it. The protective function of the covenant boundary: the new covenant community lives within the boundaries of the covenant &#8212; not crossing into the world&#8217;s patterns of exploitation, not allowing the world&#8217;s patterns to cross into the community. Eph 4:17&#8211;18 &#8212; &#8220;you must no longer live as the Gentiles do.&#8221; The boundary that Jacob and Laban establish is the type of the covenant boundary that defines the church&#8217;s distinctive identity.</p>",
"53": "<p>&#8220;May the God of Abraham and the God of Nahor, the God of their father, judge between us.&#8221; Jacob swears by &#8220;the Awe of his father Isaac&#8221; &#8212; the divine title of v42 &#8212; rather than by the common ancestor&#8217;s God. The choice of divine title is significant: Jacob swears not by the God that both families acknowledge but by the specific covenant name that belongs to his line &#8212; the God who revealed himself distinctively to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. The covenant God is not merely the highest common denominator of all religious traditions; he is the specific God who made specific promises to specific people, fulfilled in the specific person of Jesus Christ (Acts 4:12 &#8212; &#8220;there is no other name&#8221;).</p>",
"54": "<p>Jacob offered a sacrifice on the hill and invited his relatives to a meal &#8212; the covenant meal that seals the covenant agreement. The sacrifice and meal as the completion of the covenant: Exod 24:3&#8211;11 (the Sinai covenant sealed with sacrifice and a meal on the mountain before God). The covenant meal is the pattern of the Lord&#8217;s Supper &#8212; the sacrifice of Christ sealed in his blood, the meal shared by the covenant community in remembrance. Every covenant meal in the OT &#8212; here at Gilead, at Sinai, the Passover &#8212; points toward the one covenant meal that the new covenant community shares &#8220;until he comes&#8221; (1 Cor 11:26).</p>",
"55": "<p>Laban rose early, kissed his grandchildren and daughters, blessed them, and returned home. The final parting &#8212; Laban&#8217;s genuine affection for his family expressed in the blessing-kiss at departure. The covenant chapter ends with blessing, not curse: the conflict that threatened to become violent has been resolved by divine intervention and covenant-making. The God who protected Jacob from Laban&#8217;s wrath also gave Laban the chance to bless rather than curse. The capacity to bless at departure &#8212; even after conflict &#8212; is the grace of covenant resolution. Rom 12:14 &#8212; &#8220;bless those who persecute you; bless and do not curse.&#8221;</p>"
},
"32": {
"1": "<p>&#8220;Jacob also went on his way, and the angels of God met him.&#8221; The departed Laban is replaced immediately by the presence of the angels of God &#8212; the divine escort takes the place of the human pursuer. The covenant heir who was accompanied by threat is now accompanied by the divine army. Heb 1:14 &#8212; &#8220;are not all angels ministering spirits sent to serve those who will inherit salvation?&#8221; The angelic presence that meets Jacob on the way back to Canaan is the covenant community&#8217;s invisible escort: &#8220;the angel of the LORD encamps around those who fear him, and he delivers them&#8221; (Ps 34:7).</p>",
"2": "<p>&#8220;This is the camp of God!&#8221; &#8212; Jacob names the place Mahanaim (two camps). The double camp &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s visible camp and the divine invisible camp &#8212; is the structure of the covenant community&#8217;s existence. The church is always both a visible, human community and the dwelling place of the divine presence. 2 Kgs 6:17 &#8212; Elisha&#8217;s servant sees &#8220;the hills full of horses and chariots of fire all around Elisha&#8221; &#8212; the invisible divine army revealed. The &#8220;two camps&#8221; of Mahanaim are the visible and invisible reality of the church: the human community surrounded by the divine presence.</p>",
"3": "<p>Jacob sent messengers ahead to Esau in Seir &#8212; the preparatory diplomacy before the feared meeting. The reconciliation that must come &#8212; twenty years after the stolen blessing, the brothers must meet. Jacob takes the initiative in seeking reconciliation even though Esau wronged himself by despising his birthright (25:34) and Jacob wronged Esau by the deception. The one who takes the initiative in reconciliation, even when the other is partly at fault: Matt 5:23&#8211;24 &#8212; &#8220;if you are offering your gift at the altar and there remember that your brother or sister has something against you, leave your gift there&#8230; first go and be reconciled.&#8221;</p>",
"4": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s diplomatic message is crafted with care &#8212; self-effacing (&#8220;your servant Jacob&#8221;) and informative (accounting for the twenty-year absence). The careful speech before the feared encounter: Prov 15:1 &#8212; &#8220;a gentle answer turns away wrath, but a harsh word stirs up anger.&#8221; Jacob approaches Esau not with the pride of the covenant heir who received the blessing but with the humility of one who knows reconciliation costs something. The model of approaching those from whom estrangement exists with self-effacing, informative honesty rather than assertion of rights.</p>",
"5": "<p>Jacob reports his accumulated wealth &#8212; cattle, donkeys, flocks, servants. The covenant blessing made visible. The wealth Jacob announces is not boasting but disclosure &#8212; establishing that he is not returning as a beggar seeking Esau&#8217;s charity but as a man of substance. The motive is to make clear that he wants reconciliation, not resources. The one who approaches for reconciliation establishes that the approach is not self-interested but genuinely seeking the other&#8217;s good: Phil 2:3&#8211;4 &#8212; &#8220;in humility value others above yourselves, not looking to your own interests but each of you to the interests of the others.&#8221;</p>",
"6": "<p>The messengers return: Esau is coming with four hundred men. Jacob&#8217;s worst fear &#8212; the brother who swore to kill him is bringing an army. The &#8220;great fear and distress&#8221; of v7 is the reasonable response. The coming of the feared brother with an army is the crisis that drives Jacob to his greatest prayer (vv9&#8211;12). The threats that drive the covenant community to prayer are the threats that become the occasions of the greatest divine manifestations. The four hundred men who terrify Jacob are the four hundred men who will be astonished by the reconciliation (ch33). The threat becomes the occasion of grace.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;In great fear and distress Jacob divided the people&#8230; into two groups.&#8221; The strategic response to the threat &#8212; divide so that if one is attacked, the other escapes. The human wisdom of contingency planning in the face of threat. Jacob does not abandon wisdom for passive fatalism; he makes human preparations while also praying (vv9&#8211;12). The integration of prayer and practical preparation: &#8220;pray as if everything depends on God; work as if everything depends on you&#8221; &#8212; a principle embedded in the Nehemiah model (Neh 4:9 &#8212; &#8220;we prayed to our God and posted a guard day and night&#8221;). The two groups are the contingency; the prayer is the foundation.</p>",
"8": "<p>&#8220;If Esau comes and attacks one group, the group that is left may escape.&#8221; The safety provision embedded in the division &#8212; the survival instinct that protects the covenant heir and his household. The preservation of a remnant: Isa 10:20&#8211;21 (the remnant of Israel will return to the Mighty God). The divine purpose of preserving a remnant through every catastrophe runs from Noah (6:8) through Jacob&#8217;s two-group strategy through the exile remnant to Paul&#8217;s &#8220;remnant chosen by grace&#8221; (Rom 11:5). Jacob&#8217;s contingency plan unknowingly participates in the divine pattern of remnant-preservation.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;O God of my father Abraham, God of my father Isaac, LORD, who said to me, &#8216;Go back to your country and your relatives, and I will make you prosper.&#8217;&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s prayer begins with the covenant name and the covenant promise &#8212; he grounds his petition in what God has already said and done. This is the model of intercessory prayer: appeal to divine promise rather than personal merit, appeal to the character revealed in the covenant name rather than to general principles. Luke 18:7 &#8212; &#8220;will not God bring about justice for his chosen ones, who cry out to him day and night?&#8221; The prayer of v9 is the cry of the chosen one appealing to the God who called him.</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;I am unworthy of all the kindness and faithfulness you have shown your servant. I had only my staff when I crossed this Jordan, but now I have become two camps.&#8221; The model of humble prayer &#8212; acknowledging unworthiness before appealing to divine grace. The one who crossed the Jordan with only a staff now has two camps &#8212; the contrast frames the confession: all of it is the gift of divine <em>ḥesed</em> (covenant love) and <em>ʾemet</em> (faithfulness). The self-abasement before divine grace is the ground of the appeal: Luke 18:13 &#8212; &#8220;God, have mercy on me, a sinner&#8221; &#8212; the prayer that is heard precisely because it does not claim merit.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;Save me, I pray, from the hand of my brother Esau, for I am afraid he will come and attack me, and also the mothers with their children.&#8221; The specific, honest petition &#8212; Jacob names the exact threat and the ones most vulnerable: the mothers with their children. The prayer that names specific, concrete needs rather than speaking in vague generalities: Phil 4:6 &#8212; &#8220;in every situation, by prayer and petition, with thanksgiving, present your requests to God.&#8221; The inclusion of the vulnerable &#8212; &#8220;the mothers with their children&#8221; &#8212; in the petition mirrors Christ&#8217;s concern for the most vulnerable (Matt 18:3&#8211;6; 19:13&#8211;15).</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;But you have said, &#8216;I will surely make you prosper and will make your descendants like the sand of the sea.&#8217;&#8221; Jacob concludes his prayer by returning to the divine promise &#8212; the appeal to what God has spoken as the ground of the petition. The theological move of reminding God of his own promise is not correcting a forgetful God but aligning the petitioner&#8217;s faith with what God has declared. Heb 10:23 &#8212; &#8220;let us hold unswervingly to the hope we profess, for he who promised is faithful.&#8221; The prayer of v12 holds to the covenant promise as the ground of hope in the face of the armed threat of v6.</p>",
"13": "<p>After the prayer, Jacob selected gifts for Esau &#8212; prayer followed by practical preparation. The integration of petition and action: prayer does not replace prudent human effort but undergirds and directs it. The generous gift selection &#8212; &#8220;he selected a gift for his brother Esau&#8221; from what he had &#8212; is the generosity of one who has been given much (vv9&#8211;10) now giving to the one he has wronged. Zacchaeus after the encounter with Christ: &#8220;half of my possessions I give to the poor, and if I have cheated anybody out of anything, I will pay back four times the amount&#8221; (Luke 19:8). Reconciliation includes restitution.</p>",
"14": "<p>Two hundred female goats and twenty male goats, two hundred ewes and twenty rams &#8212; the beginning of an extraordinary gift. The scale of Jacob&#8217;s generosity: 550 animals in total (counting through v15). The extravagant peace offering to the one he has wronged. The parable of the prodigal son&#8217;s father: &#8220;quick! Bring the best robe and put it on him. Put a ring on his finger and sandals on his feet. Bring the fattened calf and kill it&#8221; (Luke 15:22&#8211;23) &#8212; the father&#8217;s extravagance toward the returning son. Jacob&#8217;s extravagance toward Esau mirrors the divine extravagance toward those who return.</p>",
"15": "<p>Thirty female camels with their young, forty cows, ten bulls, twenty female donkeys, ten male donkeys &#8212; completing the gift calculation. The gift that equals or exceeds the livestock categories that Jacob reported in v5. Jacob gives back from the abundance that God gave him during the exile &#8212; the gift is from God&#8217;s provision, not from Jacob&#8217;s own natural resources. 2 Cor 9:8 &#8212; &#8220;God is able to bless you abundantly, so that in all things at all times, having all that you need, you will abound in every good work.&#8221; The extravagant generosity that reconciliation requires comes from the abundance that God supplies.</p>",
"16": "<p>Jacob sends the herds in separate waves, each with space between &#8212; the strategy of accumulating the impression of generosity. The repeated arrival of gift-herds will have greater emotional impact than a single large group. The strategic wisdom of the approach &#8212; not deception but effective communication of genuine intent. The &#8220;wisdom of the serpent, innocence of the dove&#8221; (Matt 10:16) &#8212; using skill and timing to communicate what is genuinely meant. The waves of gifts are designed to soften Esau&#8217;s anger before the face-to-face meeting.</p>",
"17": "<p>Instructions to the lead servant about how to respond to Esau&#8217;s questions. The careful preparation of the message &#8212; the gift-herds are ambassadors carrying a specific message, rehearsed in advance. The church as ambassadors carrying a rehearsed message: 2 Cor 5:20 &#8212; &#8220;we are therefore Christ&#8217;s ambassadors, as though God were making his appeal through us.&#8221; The message of reconciliation that the ambassadors carry is rehearsed, specific, and grounded in the sender&#8217;s genuine intent. The message of v18 &#8212; &#8220;they are a gift sent to my lord Esau&#8221; &#8212; is the message of the gospel: freely given, not earned.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;They belong to your servant Jacob; they are a gift sent to my lord Esau.&#8221; The self-effacing identification and the gift &#8212; the combination of humility (&#8220;your servant&#8221;, &#8220;my lord&#8221;) and generosity (&#8220;a gift&#8221;). The vocabulary of servanthood in the approach to reconciliation. Phil 2:5&#8211;8 &#8212; the mind of Christ: &#8220;who, being in very nature God, did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage&#8230; he made himself nothing by taking the very nature of a servant.&#8221; The self-emptying approach to the other, offering gifts rather than asserting rights, is the posture of incarnational reconciliation.</p>",
"19": "<p>The same instruction to the second, third, and all subsequent herd-leaders: identical message, consistent testimony. The consistent, repeated message of reconciliation &#8212; not improvised but rehearsed, reliable, the same from every messenger. The apostolic gospel is similarly consistent: &#8220;whether it was I or they, this is what we preach, and this is what you believed&#8221; (1 Cor 15:11). The gift that Jacob sends is not one spontaneous gesture but a carefully prepared, consistently communicated act of reconciliation. The message of the cross is the same message from every authentic witness.</p>",
"20": "<p>&#8220;I will pacify him with these gifts I am sending on ahead; later, when I see him, perhaps he will receive me.&#8221; Jacob&#8217;s hope &#8212; the gifts going ahead to prepare the way for the person. The gift that precedes and prepares the way for the giver&#8217;s arrival: the Holy Spirit as the gift sent ahead of the final coming of Christ &#8212; &#8220;the Spirit of truth, whom the world cannot receive&#8221; (John 14:17), sent ahead to prepare the world for the full revelation at Christ&#8217;s return. The gifts that go before Jacob soften Esau&#8217;s heart; the Spirit that goes before Christ prepares hearts to receive him.</p>",
"21": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s gifts go ahead, but he himself spent the night in the camp &#8212; alone, in the dark, waiting. The covenant heir in the place of solitary waiting before the decisive encounter. This is the stillness before Peniel &#8212; the last night of Jacob&#8217;s old identity before the name-change of v28. Gethsemane: &#8220;he withdrew about a stone&#8217;s throw beyond them, knelt down and prayed&#8221; (Luke 22:41). The solitary night-watch before the decisive moment is the pattern of the covenant heir at the hinge of history: Jacob at the Jabbok, Moses at Sinai, Elijah under the broom tree, Jesus in Gethsemane.</p>",
"22": "<p>Jacob rose in the night and took his wives, servants, and eleven sons across the Jabbok ford &#8212; sending everything he had across before remaining alone on the other side. The deliberate isolation: Jacob clears the ford of all that is his so that he alone remains. The stripping away of everything that might be a security or distraction before the divine encounter. The desert spirituality of the NT: Jesus driven into the wilderness (Matt 4:1); Paul going to Arabia after his conversion (Gal 1:17). The Jabbok crossing is the preparation for Peniel: you cannot wrestle with God while managing a crowd.</p>",
"23": "<p>After sending all his possessions across, Jacob was left alone on the far bank. The deliberateness of the solitude &#8212; Jacob is not accidentally alone but strategically so. The last thing to cross the ford is Jacob&#8217;s security; the first thing that remains is Jacob himself. The stripping down to the essential self before God &#8212; not Jacob the provider, the schemer, the wealthy patriarch, but simply Jacob. Ps 46:10 &#8212; &#8220;be still, and know that I am God.&#8221; The stillness that precedes divine encounter requires the deliberate setting aside of the roles and possessions that ordinarily define the self.</p>",
"24": "<p>&#8220;A man wrestled with him till daybreak.&#8221; The wrestling at the Jabbok &#8212; one of the most theologically dense scenes in Genesis. The &#8220;man&#8221; who wrestles with Jacob all night is identified as divine: v30 (&#8220;I saw God face to face&#8221;) and Hosea 12:3&#8211;5 (&#8220;he struggled with the angel&#8230; the LORD God Almighty&#8221;). Many church fathers (Justin Martyr, Tertullian, Origen) and later theologians (Calvin) read this as a Christophany &#8212; the pre-incarnate Son of God in physical encounter with Jacob. John 8:56 (&#8220;Abraham rejoiced at the thought of seeing my day; he saw it and was glad&#8221;) suggests the patriarchal theophanies involve the Son. The incarnation is not the first time God takes human form; it is the permanent form.</p>",
"25": "<p>&#8220;When the man saw that he could not overpower him, he touched the socket of Jacob&#8217;s hip so that his hip was wrenched.&#8221; The divine self-limitation in the wrestling encounter &#8212; the one who is omnipotent cannot overpower Jacob without intervening miraculously. The wrestling is genuinely contested until the divine intervenient touch. The kenosis of Phil 2:7 &#8212; God &#8220;made himself nothing&#8221; in the incarnation &#8212; is the permanent form of the divine self-limitation that the Jabbok wrestling shows momentarily. The God who limits himself to be encountered by human beings is the God who limits himself permanently in Christ. The touch of the hip is the divine assertion that the limitation is chosen, not necessary.</p>",
"26": "<p>&#8220;Let me go, for it is daybreak.&#8221; &#8220;I will not let you go unless you bless me.&#8221; The climactic moment &#8212; Jacob clinging to the divine wrestler and refusing to release without the blessing. Luke 18:1&#8211;8 &#8212; the parable of the persistent widow who &#8220;kept coming&#8221; to the judge: &#8220;will not God bring about justice for his chosen ones, who cry out to him day and night?&#8221; The faith that holds on despite pain (Jacob&#8217;s wrenched hip), despite the approaching dawn, despite the implicit threat in the divine request &#8212; and refuses to release without the blessing. This is the faith that &#8220;overcomes&#8221; (Rev 2:7, 11, 17, 26) &#8212; the persistent clinging to God that wins the blessing.</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;What is your name?&#8221; &#8220;Jacob.&#8221; The divine question already knows the answer &#8212; the name &#8220;Jacob&#8221; is about to be changed. The question &#8220;what is your name?&#8221; invites the naming of the old identity before the new one is given. The self-identification as Jacob &#8212; &#8220;the supplanter,&#8221; the deceiver, the heel-grabber &#8212; is the honest acknowledgment of who he has been. Confession of the old identity is the prerequisite for the new name. Rev 2:17 &#8212; &#8220;to the one who is victorious, I will give&#8230; a new name written on it, known only to the one who receives it.&#8221; The new name requires the acknowledgment of the old.</p>",
"28": "<p>&#8220;Your name will no longer be Jacob, but Israel, because you have struggled with God and with humans and have overcome.&#8221; The name-change that defines the covenant people: <em>Yiśrāʾēl</em> &#8212; &#8220;one who strives with God&#8221; or &#8220;God prevails.&#8221; The new identity given in the encounter with Christ &#8212; 2 Cor 5:17: &#8220;if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: the old has gone, the new is here!&#8221; Rev 2:17 &#8212; the new name. Heb 11:21 notes Jacob as a man of faith. The covenant people take their identity not from their natural origin (<em>Jacob</em> = supplanter) but from their encounter with God (<em>Israel</em> = one who strives with God). The church&#8217;s identity is defined by its encounter with Christ, not its human origin.</p>",
"29": "<p>&#8220;Please tell me your name.&#8221; &#8220;Why do you ask my name?&#8221; The divine name withheld &#8212; the mystery of the divine identity preserved even in the moment of intimate encounter. Exod 3:14 &#8212; &#8220;I AM WHO I AM&#8221; &#8212; the name that is both revealed and beyond complete articulation. John 8:58 &#8212; &#8220;before Abraham was born, I am!&#8221; &#8212; Christ&#8217;s appropriation of the divine name. The one who wrestled with Jacob and declined to give his name is the one whose name is above every name (Phil 2:9): &#8220;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow.&#8221; The name withheld at Jabbok is the name fully revealed in the resurrection of Christ.</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;It is because I saw God face to face, and yet my life was spared.&#8221; Jacob names the place Peniel &#8212; &#8220;face of God.&#8221; The paradox of seeing God face to face and living: Exod 33:20 &#8212; &#8220;you cannot see my face, for no one may see me and live.&#8221; Yet Jacob lives. 2 Cor 4:6 &#8212; &#8220;God, who said, &#8216;Let light shine out of darkness,&#8217; made his light shine in our hearts to give us the light of the knowledge of God&#8217;s glory displayed in the face of Christ.&#8221; The face of God that cannot be seen directly is the face that shines &#8220;in the face of Christ&#8221; &#8212; the full divine glory made bearable in the incarnation. Peniel anticipates the incarnation: the place where God&#8217;s face is seen and life is preserved, not lost.</p>",
"31": "<p>The sun rose above him as he passed Peniel &#8212; limping because of his hip. The dawn that follows the night of wrestling, the light after the darkness. The new day that comes after the encounter with God carries the mark of the encounter: the limp that remains. The wound that the encounter leaves &#8212; not punitive but identifying. Paul&#8217;s thorn in the flesh (2 Cor 12:7&#8211;9) has the same structure: the mark left by divine encounter that keeps the person humble and dependent: &#8220;my grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.&#8221; The limp is not a punishment for the wrestling but the permanent mark of the one who has wrestled with God and overcome.</p>",
"32": "<p>The dietary restriction &#8212; the Israelites do not eat the tendon on the hip socket &#8212; is the communal practice of remembering the Peniel encounter. The covenant community&#8217;s food practice encodes the memory of the patriarch&#8217;s transforming encounter with God. The Lord&#8217;s Supper operates on the same principle: &#8220;do this in remembrance of me&#8221; (Luke 22:19) &#8212; a food practice that encodes the memory of Christ&#8217;s decisive encounter with human sin and death. The tendon not eaten is Israel&#8217;s embodied memory of Peniel; the bread and cup are the church&#8217;s embodied memory of the cross. Both food practices are covenant mnemonics encoded in the body.</p>"
}
}

